I received a 2 out of 8 in theatre because my voice was described as “too girly” and not satisfying the role of a leader. I believe this feedback raises an important concern about how leadership is defined. Leadership should not be limited to a deep or traditionally masculine voice. Authority can also be expressed through clarity, intention, and emotional control.

The comment about my voice sounding “girly” feels subjective and possibly based on stereotypes about how leaders are expected to sound. In modern theatre, leaders can be calm, strategic, or emotionally intelligent, not only loud and dominant. A higher-pitched voice does not automatically mean weakness.

If the assessment focused mainly on vocal tone rather than character interpretation, stage presence, and delivery technique, then the grading criteria may not have been fully balanced. Constructive feedback should explain how to improve specific techniques instead of labeling a natural voice quality as unsuitable.

I believe theatre should allow different interpretations of leadership, and evaluation should reflect diversity in expression rather than a single standard.
